===Beginning===
Google began as a research project in January, 1996 by [[Lawrence E. Page|Larry Page]] and [[Sergey Brin]], two [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] students at [[Stanford University|Stanford]].<ref>[http://www.google.com/intl/en/corporate/history.html Google Corporate History].</ref> They hypothesized that a search engine that analyzed the relationships between websites would produce better results than existing techniques (existing search engines at the time essentially ranked results according to how many times the search term appeared on a page).<ref>Page, Lawrence; Brin, Sergey; Motwani, Rajeev; Winograd, Terry. "[http://dbpubs.stanford.edu:8090/pub/1999-66 The PageRank Citation Ranking: Bringing Order to the Web]." [[November 11]], [[1999]].</ref> It was originally nicknamed, "BackRub," because the system checked [[backlinks]] to estimate a site's importance.<ref>Battelle, John. "[http://www.wired.com/wired/archive/13.08/battelle.html?tw=wn_tophead_4 The Birth of Google]." ''[[Wired Magazine]].'' August, 2005.</ref> A small search engine called '''RankDex''' was already exploring a similar strategy.<ref>Li, Yanhong. "[http://dx.doi.org/10.1109/4236.707687 Toward a qualitative search engine]." ''Internet Computing, IEEE.'' '''2 (4),''' July-August, 1998, 24-29.</ref>
